Part I - (Loan Data Exploration)¶

by (Agbons Ekata-Inuaghata)¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset containing 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

The dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 features (including LoanOriginalAmount, BorrowerAPR, Borrower Rate, Occupation, Available Bank Credit, StatedMonthlyIncome, Term, ProsperRating (Alpha), EmploymentStatus and many others)

I'm most interested in figuring out the best features for predicting the borrower's interest rate for the loan.

I expect that features such as the 'total loan amount, 'available bank credit, salary range' etc will have a negative effect on the borrowerrate of the loan: the larger the total loan amount, the lower the interest rate. I also strongly feel that the 'stated monthly income' of the borrower, loan term, Prosper rating, Prosper Score, occupation, and the employment status will also have effects on the interest rate.

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by understanding and exploring the distribution of the main variable of interest: borrower rate.

In [95]:

The distribution of borrower rate looks bimodal. The highest point is at around 0.15 and the second peak is at around 0.32. No loans have interest rates up to 0.4

Less than 0.3 percent of the borrowers have stated monthly income greater than 30k. These can be seen as outliers for the following analysis, so it is better to remove borrower records with income greater than 30k.

Bivariate Exploration¶

To start off with, I want to explore the relationship between year and borrrower rate across the years, then the pairwise correlations present between various features in the data.

In [277]:
g = sb.PairGrid(data = loan, vars = numeric_vars)
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist, bins=20)
g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter, alpha=0.2);

  • There is a negative correlation between Borrowerrate and Original Loan Amount. This means that the higher the loan amount, the lower the interest rate. This will encourage borrowers to take more loans

  • The loan original amount is positively correlated with the stated monthly income, it makes sense since borrowers with more monthly income could loan more money

  • There is a negative correlation between Borrowerrate and Available Bank card credit. This means that the higher the available credit the borrower has, the lower the interest rate.

In [267]:
#Convert Employment status a nd income rangeinto ordered categories
order_of_employment = ['Employed','Self-employed','Full-time','Part-time','Retired','Other','Not employed', 'Not available']
ordered_emp_rating = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = order_of_employment)
loan.employmentstatus = loan.employmentstatus.astype(ordered_emp_rating)

#Income range
income_range = ['Not displayed', 'Not employed', '$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999', '$50,000-74999', '$75,000-99,999',
               '$100,000+']
ordered_income = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = income_range)
loan.incomerange = loan.incomerange.astype(ordered_income)
In [276]:
def box_plot_grid(x, y, **kwargs):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = base_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90)
    
plt.figure(figsize = [20, 10]);
g = sb.PairGrid(data = loan, x_vars = categorical, y_vars = numeric, size = 3, aspect = 1.5);
g.map(box_plot_grid);

<Figure size 1440x720 with 0 Axes>

  • From the figure above, we can infer that borrower rate is steady across income ranges, higher income ranges have higher available credits in the bank along with higher stated monthly incomes, but borrower rate seems to be slightly lower for higher earners. Finally, the higher the income range, the higher the original loan amount

  • We can also see from our boxplot that borrowers who completed their loans have higher available bank credits than all other categories, whilst also having mimimal interest rates between 0.1 and 0.3

  • From our boxplot, we can observe that the loam amount was steady between 2005-2012, but increased significantly between 2013-2014. The borrower rate fluctuated between 2006-2010, but has been gradually decreasing since 2011 to 2014.

  • We can also infer that Employed, Self-employed, and full time individuals have higher monthly incomes than other categories. This category of people also have higher borroweraprs and have higher loan amounts

I want to see how borrower rate relates with loan original amount and available bank credit for all of the data.

  • The first plot shows that the borrower rate is negatively correlated with loan amount. The higher the loan amount, the lower the interest rate
  • The second plot shows that that the borrower rate is negatively correlated with the available bank card credit. The interest rate is negative at some point for bank card credits from 20000 to 60000 plus. Negative borrower interest rates encourage borrowers with higher bank card credits to borrow more

Borrower rate is negatively correlated with loan amount. The higher the loan amount, the lower the interest rate. borrowers who completed their loans have higher available bank credits than all other categories, whilst also having mimimal interest rates between 0.1 and 0.3. The loan original amount is positively correlated with the stated monthly income, it makes sense since borrowers with more monthly income could loan more money. It also shows that borrowers with better rating also have larger monthly income and loan amount.

The higher the income range, the higher the original loan amount. Employed, Self-employed, and full time individuals have higher monthly incomes than other categories. This category of people also have lower borrowerrates, have higher loan amounts and available bank credits

Multivariate Exploration¶

The main point of exploration in this part of the analysis is how the categorical variables (Prosper rating, year, homeowner status, employment status and term) play into the relationship between borrowerrate and loan original amount.

In [230]:
plt.figure(figsize = [10, 8]);
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = loan, col = 'year', col_wrap = 4);
g.map(sb.regplot, 'loanoriginalamount', 'borrowerrate', scatter_kws={'alpha':0.01});
g.add_legend();

<Figure size 720x576 with 0 Axes>

Aside from year 2005 which is an outlier because it has just 22 entries, Borrower rate seems to have a negative correlation with original loan amount across all other years. Another observation here is that there is a gradual increase in the loan amounts across the years

In this final section, we expand our research of interest rate against loan amount by observing the impact of third variables such as the income range, year, employment status, loan status, number of loans taken, and home ownership status.

  • The multivariate exploration showed that There is a gradual increase in the loam amount as the income range increases. People with higher income ranges borrow more and people with lower incomes borrow less. The borrower rate also seems to reduce very slightly as income range increases

  • Borrower rate seems to have a negative correlation with original loan amount across all other years. Another observation here is that there is a gradual increase in the loan amounts across the years

  • Individuals with more number of loans seem to have borrowed less than others with fewer number of loans.
